---
import { ArrowRight, Info, X, Zap } from 'lucide-react'
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro'
import Navbar from '../components/Navbar.astro'
import PricingComponent from '../components/Pricing.astro'
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro'
---

<Layout
  title="Pricing | Tracehound"
  description="Simple, predictable pricing for enterprise-grade security."
>
  <Navbar />

  <!-- Pricing Hero -->
  <section class="pt-32 pb-16">
    <div class="container-custom">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center">
        <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-6xl font-bold mb-6 tracking-tight">
          One ecosystem.<br />
          <span class="text-text-muted">Different missions.</span>
        </h1>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-lg mb-12 max-w-2xl mx-auto">
          Tracehound isolates runtime threats. Argos detects behavioral anomalies. Both are priced
          independently — choose what fits your security posture.
        </p>

        <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-6 justify-center">
          <a
            href="#pricing"
            class="group px-6 py-4 bg-surface/50 border border-primary/30 hover:border-primary/50 rounded-sm transition-all"
          >
            <div class="text-xs text-text-muted uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 font-mono">
              The Core
            </div>
            <div
              class="text-xl font-bold text-white group-hover:text-primary transition-colors font-mono"
            >
              Tracehound
            </div>
            <div class="text-sm text-text-muted mt-1">
              From <span class="text-primary">$9</span> to <span class="text-white">$499/mo</span>
            </div>
          </a>

          <a
            href="#argos"
            class="group px-6 py-4 bg-purple-500/5 border border-purple-500/20 hover:border-purple-500/50 rounded-sm transition-all"
          >
            <div class="text-xs text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 font-mono">
              The Observer
            </div>
            <div
              class="text-xl font-bold text-white group-hover:text-purple-400 transition-colors font-mono"
            >
              Argos
            </div>
            <div class="text-sm text-text-muted mt-1">
              <span class="text-purple-400">$49/mo</span> standalone
            </div>
          </a>
        </div>

        <div
          class="mt-8 inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 bg-surface/30 border border-surface-highlight rounded-sm text-sm text-text-muted"
        >
          <span class="w-2 h-2 bg-primary rounded-full"></span>
          <span>Priced per logical service — not per request, not per replica.</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <PricingComponent />

  <!-- Argos Section -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface/30 border-y border-surface-highlight" id="argos">
    <div class="container-custom">
      <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto">
        <div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-16 items-start">
          <div class="flex-1">
            <div
              class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-3 py-1 rounded-sm border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-500/10 text-purple-400 text-xs font-mono mb-6"
            >
              SEPARATE PRODUCT
            </div>
            <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-bold mb-4 font-mono tracking-tight">Argos</h2>
            <p class="text-xl text-purple-400 font-medium mb-2 font-mono">
              Runtime Deviation Signals
            </p>
            <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">Licensed and operated independently from Tracehound.</p>

            <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-6 mb-8">
              <div>
                <div class="flex items-baseline gap-1">
                  <span class="text-4xl font-bold text-white">$49</span>
                  <span class="text-text-muted text-lg">/ month</span>
                </div>
                <p class="text-xs text-text-muted font-mono">Standalone</p>
              </div>
              <div class="hidden sm:block w-px bg-purple-500/30"></div>
              <div>
                <div class="flex items-baseline gap-1">
                  <span class="text-4xl font-bold text-white">+$29</span>
                  <span class="text-text-muted text-lg">/ month</span>
                </div>
                <p class="text-xs text-text-muted font-mono">With Tracehound Pro</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="prose prose-invert prose-sm text-text-muted mb-8">
              <p>
                Argos is a <strong class="text-white">security signal layer</strong> that detects <strong
                  class="text-white">runtime deviation outside the request lifecycle</strong
                >.
              </p>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-4 space-y-1">
                <li>It does not inspect payloads.</li>
                <li>It does not detect attacks.</li>
                <li>It does not take action.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Argos exists to surface <strong class="text-white"
                  >security-relevant behavior that happens <em>between</em> requests</strong
                >.
              </p>
            </div>

            <p
              class="text-text-muted mb-8 italic border-l-2 border-purple-500/50 pl-4 py-2 font-mono text-sm"
            >
              "Argos detects when the runtime starts behaving differently — not why."
            </p>

            <button
              class="px-8 py-3 bg-purple-500/10 hover:bg-purple-500/20 text-purple-300 rounded-sm font-medium transition-colors border border-purple-500/30 hover:border-purple-500/60 w-full md:w-auto flex items-center gap-2"
            >
              Get started with Argos <ArrowRight size={18} />
            </button>
          </div>

          <div class="flex-1 w-full space-y-12">
            <!-- Grid of Details -->
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
              <div>
                <h4
                  class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-white mb-4 flex items-center gap-2 font-mono"
                >
                  <Zap className="h-4 w-4 text-purple-400" /> What Argos Does
                </h4>
                <p class="text-sm text-text-muted mb-4">
                  Argos samples the runtime and emits <strong>behavioral signals</strong> when something
                  deviates from expected behavior. It observes:
                </p>
                <ul class="space-y-2">
                  {
                    [
                      'Runtime integrity drift',
                      'Event loop and scheduling anomalies',
                      'Worker / child process behavior changes',
                      'Internal communication pattern shifts (shape, not content)',
                    ].map((item) => (
                      <li class="text-sm text-text-muted flex items-start gap-2">
                        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-purple-400 mt-2 shrink-0" />
                        {item}
                      </li>
                    ))
                  }
                </ul>
                <p class="text-xs text-purple-300 mt-4 font-mono">
                  Signal: "Did something behave differently than it should have?"
                </p>
              </div>

              <div>
                <h4
                  class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-white mb-4 flex items-center gap-2 font-mono"
                >
                  <X className="h-4 w-4 text-red-400" /> What Argos Does Not Do
                </h4>
                <p class="text-sm text-text-muted mb-4">Argos never:</p>
                <ul class="space-y-2">
                  {
                    [
                      'Classifies threats',
                      'Produces evidence',
                      'Blocks or mutates execution',
                      'Influences request latency',
                    ].map((item) => (
                      <li class="text-sm text-text-muted flex items-start gap-2">
                        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-red-400 mt-2 shrink-0" />
                        {item}
                      </li>
                    ))
                  }
                </ul>
                <p class="text-xs text-text-muted mt-4 font-mono">
                  Signals are <strong>advisory</strong> and must be validated by external systems.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="pt-8 border-t border-surface-highlight">
              <h4
                class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-white mb-4 flex items-center gap-2 font-mono"
              >
                <Info className="h-4 w-4 text-blue-400" /> Why Separate Product?
              </h4>
              <div class="bg-surface/50 p-6 rounded-sm border border-surface-highlight">
                <p class="text-sm text-text-muted mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  Argos is priced separately because it introduces a <strong class="text-white"
                    >new security observation layer</strong
                  > into your runtime. Unlike Tracehound, which preserves and isolates confirmed threats,
                  Argos emits <strong class="text-white"
                    >non-authoritative runtime deviation signals</strong
                  > that must be verified by external detectors.
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-text-muted mb-0 leading-relaxed">
                  This expands the runtime trust boundary and adds operational responsibility,
                  described in its own SLA.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- How it fits -->
            <div>
              <h4
                class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-white mb-4 flex items-center gap-2 font-mono"
              >
                How It Fits
              </h4>
              <div
                class="font-mono text-xs md:text-sm bg-black/50 p-4 rounded-sm border border-surface-highlight text-center text-text-muted"
              >
                Argos → External Detector → Threat → Tracehound
              </div>
              <div class="flex justify-between text-xs text-text-muted mt-2 px-4">
                <span>Argos produces <strong>signals</strong></span>
                <span>Tracehound handles <strong>evidence</strong></span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Why This Costs Money Section -->
  <section class="py-24">
    <div class="container-custom">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <div class="text-center mb-16">
          <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-bold mb-6 tracking-tight">Why This Costs Money</h2>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-lg max-w-2xl mx-auto">
            Tracehound is not priced on traffic, usage, or attack volume — because none of those are
            the problem it solves.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 mb-16">
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white flex items-center gap-3 font-mono">
              <span
                class="flex items-center justify-center w-8 h-8 rounded-sm bg-surface-highlight text-primary text-sm"
                >01</span
              >
              Determinism is expensive
            </h3>
            <p class="text-text-muted leading-relaxed">
              Most security tools tolerate nondeterminism: Garbage-collected memory, Retry storms,
              Best-effort async pipelines. Tracehound does not.
            </p>
            <p class="text-text-muted leading-relaxed">
              Maintaining deterministic behavior under memory pressure, pool exhaustion, and partial
              failure requires explicit ownership models, bounded degradation paths, and strictly
              constrained concurrency. This engineering effort does not scale with usage. It scales
              with <strong>correctness guarantees</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white flex items-center gap-3 font-mono">
              <span
                class="flex items-center justify-center w-8 h-8 rounded-sm bg-surface-highlight text-primary text-sm"
                >02</span
              >
              Failure semantics are designed
            </h3>
            <p class="text-text-muted leading-relaxed">
              In Tracehound, every failure mode is intentional: What degrades, What never degrades,
              What is preserved at all costs.
            </p>
            <p class="text-text-muted leading-relaxed">
              Designing and maintaining these semantics — without blocking the host application — is
              the core value of the system. This is not feature work. This is <strong
                >failure engineering</strong
              >.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white flex items-center gap-3 font-mono">
              <span
                class="flex items-center justify-center w-8 h-8 rounded-sm bg-surface-highlight text-primary text-sm"
                >03</span
              >
              Compliance requires frozen behavior
            </h3>
            <p class="text-text-muted leading-relaxed">
              Enterprise pricing exists because: Data shapes must remain stable, Evidence must
              remain verifiable, Behavior must remain explainable months or years later.
            </p>
            <p class="text-text-muted leading-relaxed">
              That requires versioned contracts and long-term support. Those guarantees have real
              cost.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white flex items-center gap-3 font-mono">
              <span
                class="flex items-center justify-center w-8 h-8 rounded-sm bg-surface-highlight text-primary text-sm"
                >04</span
              >
              Risk ownership transfer
            </h3>
            <ul class="text-text-muted space-y-2">
              <li class="flex items-center gap-2">
                <span class="w-1.5 h-1.5 bg-primary rounded-sm"></span>
                <strong>Core:</strong> you own the risk
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-center gap-2">
                <span class="w-1.5 h-1.5 bg-primary rounded-sm"></span>
                <strong>Production:</strong> risk is shared
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-center gap-2">
                <span class="w-1.5 h-1.5 bg-primary rounded-sm"></span>
                <strong>Enterprise:</strong> risk is contractually bounded
              </li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-text-muted leading-relaxed mt-2">
              The price difference reflects <strong>who is accountable when things go wrong</strong
              >.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div
          class="bg-surface/30 border border-primary/20 rounded-sm p-8 md:p-12 text-center md:text-xl font-medium leading-relaxed"
        >
          <p class="mb-4 text-white">
            If your system can tolerate undefined behavior during security incidents, you do not
            need Tracehound.
          </p>
          <p class="text-primary">If it cannot, this is what precision costs.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ CTA -->
  <section class="py-16 border-t border-surface-highlight">
    <div class="container-custom">
      <div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto text-center">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Have questions about pricing?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-muted mb-8">
          Learn about per-service pricing, Kubernetes replicas, microservices, and more.
        </p>
        <a
          href="/faq"
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-6 py-3 bg-surface-highlight text-white rounded-sm font-medium hover:bg-surface-highlight/80 transition-colors"
        >
          Read our FAQ
          <span class="text-primary">→</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
